Influenza A and B illness in humans ranges from subclinical or mild upper respiratory tract symptoms to more severe illness including laryngotracheitis and pneumonia or, less commonly, death from respiratory system failure. The most common presenting symptoms are cough, high temperature, joint pain and general malaise (Figure 3
). The rapid onset and short incubation period (about 48 h) are characteristic, though incubation can last up to 4 days. Individuals at greatest risk of complications are those with pre-existing cardiac and respiratory disease, the elderly, and those with impaired immune systems (Table 1
). The severity of the illness reflects pre-existing host immunity and the prevailing virus strain.
